WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:04.992 --> 00:00:05.700
- Hello everyone.

00:00:05.700 --> 00:00:08.510
Welcome to the
Radcliffe Institute.

00:00:08.510 --> 00:00:11.320
It's great to see so many
people out for this event.

00:00:11.320 --> 00:00:12.570
My name is Sean O'Donnell.

00:00:12.570 --> 00:00:16.020
I'm the associate director
for academic ventures.

00:00:16.020 --> 00:00:18.350
And for those of you who
don't know, academic ventures

00:00:18.350 --> 00:00:21.540
it's a group at Radcliffe
that brings together people

00:00:21.540 --> 00:00:25.620
from across the university to
discuss all kinds of issues

00:00:25.620 --> 00:00:28.800
of importance to bringing
people together to discuss ideas

00:00:28.800 --> 00:00:32.549
from different perspectives,
different disciplinary

00:00:32.549 --> 00:00:33.910
perspectives.

00:00:33.910 --> 00:00:36.560
And it's my pleasure, on
this particular project,

00:00:36.560 --> 00:00:40.740
to be working with Megan Hill
from the honoring nations

00:00:40.740 --> 00:00:44.160
project, and also to
be working with Shelley

00:00:44.160 --> 00:00:47.220
Lowe, of the Harvard University
native-american project.

00:00:47.220 --> 00:00:50.292
And we know we have some really
wonderful and important topics

00:00:50.292 --> 00:00:51.000
to address today.

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:52.920
This year at the
institute we've been

00:00:52.920 --> 00:00:56.230
looking at citizenship for
this year and for next year.

00:00:56.230 --> 00:00:58.680
And there are so
many ways in which

00:00:58.680 --> 00:01:01.230
we know that this topic,
today, deeply affects notions

00:01:01.230 --> 00:01:04.319
of citizenship on native land.

00:01:04.319 --> 00:01:07.980
I also invite you to come to
Layli Long Soldier's poetry

00:01:07.980 --> 00:01:09.750
reading this Thursday.

00:01:09.750 --> 00:01:12.300
It's also at 4:15, and
also will be in this room.

00:01:12.300 --> 00:01:14.610
And also, to our
gender conference,

00:01:14.610 --> 00:01:16.910
which is entitled, "Who belongs?

00:01:16.910 --> 00:01:19.351
Global citizenship
the 21st century."

00:01:19.351 --> 00:01:21.600
Our keynote speaker for that
is Pulitzer Prize winning

00:01:21.600 --> 00:01:24.240
novelist, Jhumpa Lahiry.

00:01:24.240 --> 00:01:26.632
And we'd love to have
you, again, explore

00:01:26.632 --> 00:01:28.590
the idea of citizenship
from many perspectives.

00:01:28.590 --> 00:01:32.520
And we know that today's
event is promising

00:01:32.520 --> 00:01:35.610
to do some really wonderful
work in understanding

00:01:35.610 --> 00:01:39.760
the ways in which the Native
American people and tribes

00:01:39.760 --> 00:01:44.370
and nations are trying to make
sense of many of the things

00:01:44.370 --> 00:01:46.720
that they have inherited
in their world.

00:01:46.720 --> 00:01:48.690
So without further
ado, I'm going

00:01:48.690 --> 00:01:52.350
to bring up Shelley Lowe,
who's going to, I think,

00:01:52.350 --> 00:01:54.570
introduce the panelists
and get us started.

00:01:54.570 --> 00:01:55.070
Thanks.

00:02:03.610 --> 00:02:13.800
- [NON-NENGLISH SPEECH]

00:02:13.800 --> 00:02:14.620
Good afternoon.

00:02:14.620 --> 00:02:15.660
My name is Shelly Lowe.

00:02:15.660 --> 00:02:17.730
I am a citizen of
the Navajo Nation.

00:02:17.730 --> 00:02:20.250
I am originally from
Ganado, Arizona.

00:02:20.250 --> 00:02:22.110
I am also currently
the executive director

00:02:22.110 --> 00:02:24.840
of the Harvard University
native-american program.

00:02:24.840 --> 00:02:27.810
I want to acknowledge quickly,
the Massachusetts people whose

00:02:27.810 --> 00:02:30.300
land we're on, but also
the Wampanoag and the Muk

00:02:30.300 --> 00:02:32.970
peoples, whose histories
are so intimately tied

00:02:32.970 --> 00:02:34.710
to this institution.

00:02:34.710 --> 00:02:36.512
Before we get started
with introductions,

00:02:36.512 --> 00:02:38.470
I'm going to ask my
colleague, Jason Packineau,

00:02:38.470 --> 00:02:42.150
to come up to say a quick
blessing for our event today.

00:02:42.150 --> 00:02:46.320
And we do ask that nobody record
or take pictures at this time.

00:02:49.370 --> 00:02:51.260
Thank you Jason.

00:02:51.260 --> 00:02:53.630
Our panel tonight,
or this evening,

00:02:53.630 --> 00:02:58.350
is part of a conversation based
on a recently published book.

00:02:58.350 --> 00:03:00.320
And unfortunately, I
didn't bring my book.

00:03:00.320 --> 00:03:03.080
But I do know one of our
speakers has his book with him.

00:03:03.080 --> 00:03:05.750
The book is The Great
Vanishing Act, Blood Quantum

00:03:05.750 --> 00:03:08.000
and the Future Native Nations.

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:10.220
And one of the editors
is with us today.

00:03:10.220 --> 00:03:12.140
Mr. Norbert Hill, and
I'm sure he will talk

00:03:12.140 --> 00:03:13.530
about it a little bit more.

00:03:13.530 --> 00:03:15.590
I encourage everyone to
take a look at the book,

00:03:15.590 --> 00:03:19.714
it talks about citizenship from
various tribal points of view.

00:03:19.714 --> 00:03:21.880
From youth point of view,
to a tribal point of view,

00:03:21.880 --> 00:03:23.342
to historical points of view.

00:03:23.342 --> 00:03:24.800
And it's very good
and will kind of

00:03:24.800 --> 00:03:27.390
guide some of our
conversation today.

00:03:27.390 --> 00:03:31.680
So on our panel today,
Professor N. Bruce Duthu,

00:03:31.680 --> 00:03:33.590
a member of the
United home a nation,

00:03:33.590 --> 00:03:36.860
is the Samson outcome
professor, and former chair

00:03:36.860 --> 00:03:39.920
of the Native American
studies at Dartmouth College.

00:03:39.920 --> 00:03:41.990
He's an internationally
recognized scholar

00:03:41.990 --> 00:03:44.180
of Native American
law and policy.

00:03:44.180 --> 00:03:47.360
Professor Duthu is the author
of Shadow Nations Tribal

00:03:47.360 --> 00:03:50.630
Sovereignty and the
Limits of Legal Pluralism.

00:03:50.630 --> 00:03:53.120
Published by Oxford
University Press.

00:03:53.120 --> 00:03:55.160
And American
Indians and the Law,

00:03:55.160 --> 00:03:57.680
published by Viking
penguin press.

00:03:57.680 --> 00:04:00.770
And he was a contributing
author of Felix Cohen's Handbook

00:04:00.770 --> 00:04:02.450
of Federal Indian Law.

00:04:02.450 --> 00:04:05.720
The leading treatise in the
field of federal Indian law.

00:04:05.720 --> 00:04:09.020
His co-edited special volume
of South Atlantic quarterly,

00:04:09.020 --> 00:04:11.750
sovereignty,
indigeneity and the law,

00:04:11.750 --> 00:04:16.130
won the 2011 council of editors
of learned journals award

00:04:16.130 --> 00:04:18.170
for best special issue.

00:04:18.170 --> 00:04:19.970
He has lectured on
indigenous rights

00:04:19.970 --> 00:04:21.950
in various parts of
the world, including

00:04:21.950 --> 00:04:26.840
Russia, China, Bolivia,
Italy, France, Australia, New

00:04:26.840 --> 00:04:29.120
Zealand, and Canada.

00:04:29.120 --> 00:04:30.180
Anywhere else?

00:04:30.180 --> 00:04:32.476
We didn't miss something?

00:04:32.476 --> 00:04:34.100
And he's been teaching
a class, or he's

00:04:34.100 --> 00:04:36.433
taught a class at the Institute
for American Indian arts

00:04:36.433 --> 00:04:38.480
in Santa Fe, New Mexico.

00:04:38.480 --> 00:04:41.000
Also on the panel
is Olivia Hoeft,

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:44.120
a citizen of the Oneida
Nation of Wisconsin,

00:04:44.120 --> 00:04:45.650
where she was born and raised.

00:04:45.650 --> 00:04:49.010
She is a contributing author
to the book, the anthology,

00:04:49.010 --> 00:04:51.530
The Great Vanishing Act,
Blood Quantum and the Future

00:04:51.530 --> 00:04:52.760
of Native Nations.

00:04:52.760 --> 00:04:57.680
And she is former Miss
Oneida, in 2014, 2015.

00:04:57.680 --> 00:05:00.320
She earned her Bachelor of
Arts from Stanford University

00:05:00.320 --> 00:05:01.820
in 2015.

00:05:01.820 --> 00:05:04.430
And currently works at Google
as an associate product

00:05:04.430 --> 00:05:06.680
marketing manager
in San Francisco,

00:05:06.680 --> 00:05:11.330
where she is also a lead of the
Google American Indian network.

00:05:11.330 --> 00:05:15.350
Also on our panel,
Tesia Zientek.

00:05:15.350 --> 00:05:18.110
She is a citizen of
the Potawatomi nation.

00:05:18.110 --> 00:05:20.630
With financial help from a
prestigious gates Millennium

00:05:20.630 --> 00:05:23.210
scholarship, she
graduated magna cum laude

00:05:23.210 --> 00:05:24.770
from the University
of Notre Dame

00:05:24.770 --> 00:05:28.310
in 2009, with a Bachelor
of Arts in English.

00:05:28.310 --> 00:05:30.620
After graduation,
Tesia spent two years

00:05:30.620 --> 00:05:33.530
teaching and running an after
school program in Puerto Rico,

00:05:33.530 --> 00:05:35.660
before pursuing her
passion for education

00:05:35.660 --> 00:05:37.160
through graduate study.

00:05:37.160 --> 00:05:39.980
In 2013, she graduated
with her master

00:05:39.980 --> 00:05:43.580
of arts in education policy
from Stanford University.

00:05:43.580 --> 00:05:45.620
To celebrate her
educational achievements,

00:05:45.620 --> 00:05:48.500
Tesia has received the
Howard Yhakis Memorial

00:05:48.500 --> 00:05:52.010
Award and the next
Gen 30 under 30 award.

00:05:52.010 --> 00:05:56.450
In October, 2015, she became the
citizen Pottawatomie nation's

00:05:56.450 --> 00:05:59.450
first director for its
new education department,

00:05:59.450 --> 00:06:02.360
which aims to help tribal
members identify and reach

00:06:02.360 --> 00:06:04.190
their educational goals.

00:06:04.190 --> 00:06:08.360
Since 2012, Tesia has also
served as Potawatomi leadership

00:06:08.360 --> 00:06:11.570
program advisor, helping to
restructure and implement

00:06:11.570 --> 00:06:14.360
curriculum for the Harvard
honoring nations award winning

00:06:14.360 --> 00:06:16.350
internship program.

00:06:16.350 --> 00:06:19.220
And lastly on our panel,
Mr. Norbert S. hill

00:06:19.220 --> 00:06:23.810
Jr., a member of the
Oneida Nation of Wisconsin.

00:06:23.810 --> 00:06:25.970
Norbert Hill recently
retired as the director

00:06:25.970 --> 00:06:29.420
of education and training for
the Oneida Nation of Wisconsin.

00:06:29.420 --> 00:06:32.000
His previous appointment
was as vice president

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:34.820
of the College of Menominee
Nation for their Green Bay

00:06:34.820 --> 00:06:36.080
campus.

00:06:36.080 --> 00:06:39.020
Mr. Hill served as the Executive
Director of the American Indian

00:06:39.020 --> 00:06:42.500
Graduate Center in New Mexico,
a nonprofit organization

00:06:42.500 --> 00:06:45.290
providing funding for American
Indians and Alaska Natives

00:06:45.290 --> 00:06:47.960
to pursue graduate and
professional degrees.

00:06:47.960 --> 00:06:50.510
Previous positions
include executive director

00:06:50.510 --> 00:06:53.480
of the American Indian science
and Engineering Society,

00:06:53.480 --> 00:06:56.090
assistant dean of students at
the University of Wisconsin,

00:06:56.090 --> 00:06:59.240
Green Bay, and the director of
the American Indian educational

00:06:59.240 --> 00:07:01.520
Opportunity Program at the
University of Colorado,

00:07:01.520 --> 00:07:02.450
Boulder.

00:07:02.450 --> 00:07:05.570
He founded winds of change in
the American Indian graduate

00:07:05.570 --> 00:07:08.370
magazine publications
of AISES [INAUDIBLE]

00:07:08.370 --> 00:07:10.520
and the American
Indian Graduate Center.

00:07:10.520 --> 00:07:13.700
He holds two honorary doctorate
from Clarkson university

00:07:13.700 --> 00:07:15.320
and Cumberland college.

00:07:15.320 --> 00:07:18.740
Passport appointments include
the Environmental Defense Fund,

00:07:18.740 --> 00:07:20.990
chair and board member of
the Smithsonian National

00:07:20.990 --> 00:07:23.000
Museum of the American Indian.

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:25.490
He is an elected member of
the United Nations trust

00:07:25.490 --> 00:07:27.620
and enrollment committee,
and currently serves

00:07:27.620 --> 00:07:30.500
on the boards of St. Norbert
college, the Wisconsin

00:07:30.500 --> 00:07:34.220
historical society, and the
Green Bay botanical gardens.

00:07:34.220 --> 00:07:38.000
In 1989, Mr. hill was awarded
the Lifetime Achievement Award

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:41.840
from the National Action council
for minorities in engineering.

00:07:41.840 --> 00:07:44.300
I would like to ask the
panelists to please come up

00:07:44.300 --> 00:07:45.650
and join us on stage.

00:08:06.569 --> 00:08:08.110
And to begin our
panel tonight, we're

00:08:08.110 --> 00:08:11.470
going to have Professor
Bruce Duthu start us off.

00:08:15.900 --> 00:08:17.430
- Thank you, and
thank you Shelly.

00:08:17.430 --> 00:08:23.220
Thank you to our native tribal
hosts on whose lands we meet.

00:08:23.220 --> 00:08:26.960
And thank you to the Institute
for hosting this event.

00:08:26.960 --> 00:08:29.190
It's a great pleasure
to be back in Cambridge.

00:08:29.190 --> 00:08:31.050
I feel badly that we're
keeping you indoors

00:08:31.050 --> 00:08:35.049
on such a gorgeous day after
the winter we've been through.

00:08:35.049 --> 00:08:37.559
So thank you for indulging us.

00:08:37.559 --> 00:08:39.630
I'm not going to say
too much at this point,

00:08:39.630 --> 00:08:43.200
because our panelists
are ready to go.

00:08:43.200 --> 00:08:46.950
I'll have a few things to
say by way of summation,

00:08:46.950 --> 00:08:49.110
and then some questions
for our panelists

00:08:49.110 --> 00:08:53.220
before we turn it over to you,
the audience, to ask questions.

00:08:53.220 --> 00:08:55.380
So the way that we're
going to proceed,

00:08:55.380 --> 00:08:58.560
each panelist will
have about 15 minutes.

00:08:58.560 --> 00:09:00.840
At least that's what I
was told that you have.

00:09:00.840 --> 00:09:04.380
About 15 minutes to
share their own comments

00:09:04.380 --> 00:09:06.510
on the topic for today.

00:09:06.510 --> 00:09:11.640
And followed by a few questions
that I've circulated to them

00:09:11.640 --> 00:09:12.450
to think about.

